    "content_hash": "sha256:582b31c8b7d797dfc28b21bade3238aebe46719e4833b01c8422801e68170f4d",
    "summary": "The Crusades (1096–1291 AD) were a series of religiously motivated military campaigns launched primarily by Western European Christians to capture and hold the Holy Land — particularly Jerusalem — from Muslim rulers, representing one of the defining episodes of medieval civilization and a major point of interaction, conflict, and cultural exchange between the Christian and Islamic worlds. Proclaimed by Pope Urban II at the Council of Clermont (1095), the crusading movement channeled the military energies of the European nobility, genuine religious devotion, economic ambition, and papal political strategy into a two-century campaign that permanently altered the eastern Mediterranean world.\n\nThe [[event:2220|First Crusade]] (1096–1099) achieved its primary objective, capturing Jerusalem and establishing the [[event:2965|Crusader states]] across modern Israel, Lebanon, and parts of Syria. Subsequent crusades — including the [[event:2222|Third Crusade]] of Richard the Lionheart and the [[event:2223|disastrous Fourth Crusade]] that sacked Constantinople — had varying objectives and outcomes. The movement eventually exhausted itself against determined Islamic resistance under [[event:2273|Saladin]] and his successors, with the [[event:3531|fall of Acre in 1291]] ending the last Crusader foothold in the Levant. The Crusades left enduring legacies: accelerating Italian city-state commercial power through eastern Mediterranean trade; transmitting Islamic and Byzantine learning to Western Europe; hardening Christian-Muslim and Christian-Jewish antagonisms; and creating a romanticized mythology of holy war that shaped European identity for centuries.",
